<div class="detail-body">
  <div class="detail-grid">
    <div class="detail-section full ab">
      <div class="slabel">◎ Overview</div>
      <p class="stext" style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.9;">AVR Assembly firmware that drives an Analog Devices AD7302 8-bit parallel DAC to synthesize sine, triangle, square, sawtooth, and trapezoid waveforms at user-programmable frequencies. Verified on oscilloscope.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div style="margin-top:2px;" class="detail-grid">
    <div class="detail-section ab2">
      <div class="slabel">⊙ System Objective</div>
      <p class="stext">Implement a software-driven digital function generator in AVR assembly that produces multiple waveform types across a programmable frequency range, driving an external parallel DAC via PORTD with precise timing control.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="detail-section">
      <div class="slabel">⊘ Design Constraints</div>
      <div class="spec-list"><div class="spec-item">Waveform data must be output via PORTD (8 data bits) with CS# pulse on PORTC pin 0 meeting AD7302 setup/hold times</div><div class="spec-item">CS# must be held low for ≥1 µs per conversion — enforced by a calibrated NOP sequence</div><div class="spec-item">Frequency is controlled by an inner delay loop; the loop count is a programmable parameter</div><div class="spec-item">Sine wave requires a pre-computed lookup table stored in program memory and accessed via LPM</div><div class="spec-item">Trapezoid wave requires a flat area subroutine that holds the output constant for N cycles</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div style="margin-top:2px;">
    <div class="detail-section full">
      <div class="slabel">⊞ System Architecture</div>
      <div class="arch-diagram">┌───────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│          SIGNAL GENERATOR ARCHITECTURE                 │
├───────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│                                                        │
│  ATmega328P                                            │
│   PORTD<span class="ah">[7:0]</span> <span class="ah2">──►</span> <span class="ah">[AD7302 DAC]</span> Data Bus (8-bit)        │
│   PORTC<span class="ah">[0]</span>   <span class="ah2">──►</span> ~CS (Chip Select, active low)        │
│                                                        │
│  Waveform Engine                                       │
│   ├─ mainLoop: output byte → pulse CS# → delay        │
│   ├─ countUp:  increment counter 0x00→0xFF            │
│   ├─ countDown: decrement 0xFF→0x00 (triangle)        │
│   ├─ flatarea: hold value N cycles (trapezoid)        │
│   └─ sine table: 256-entry LUT in .cseg               │
│                                                        │
│  Frequency Control                                     │
│   <span class="ah">[delayMs]</span>: countdown loop (r19 = freq divisor)      │
│   Higher r19 → lower frequency                        │
│                                                        │
│  <span class="ah">[AD7302]</span> <span class="ah2">──►</span> RC Low-Pass Filter <span class="ah2">──►</span> Oscilloscope     │
│                                                        │
└───────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘</div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div style="margin-top:2px;" class="detail-grid">
    <div class="detail-section ab3">
      <div class="slabel">⊛ Firmware Architecture</div>
      <p class="stext">Each waveform program follows the same pattern: load the next output value into r18, write it to PORTD, clear PORTC bit 0 (assert CS#), execute a 1-µs NOP sequence, set PORTC bit 0 (release CS#), call delayMs for frequency control, then loop. The triangle wave uses countUp/countDown subroutines alternating between incrementing and decrementing r18. The trapezoid adds a flatarea routine holding the current value for extra cycles at both peaks. The sine wave uses LPM with a Z-pointer stepping through a 256-entry sine table in .cseg. Frequency is controlled by r19's initial value — the delay loop decrements to zero so larger values produce longer delays and lower frequencies.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="detail-section abg">
      <div class="slabel">◈ Determinism &amp; Hard Real-Time Guarantees</div>
      <p class="stext">Timing determinism is achieved entirely through instruction-cycle counting. The 1-µs CS# pulse width is enforced by a NOP sequence computed from the 16 MHz clock (16 cycles = 1 µs). The delayMs inner loop executes a fixed number of cycles per count (dec + brne = 2 cycles), so the output rate is fully deterministic given the frequency divisor. No interrupts or timers are used — the waveform loop owns the CPU completely, guaranteeing jitter-free output bounded only by the DAC conversion latency.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
